In China, bronze tōsu have been discovered from the early {{ill|Erlitou culture|ja|二里頭文化}} during the {{ill|Shang dynasty|ja|殷}} period. These tōsu were typically {{ill|ring-headed|ja|環頭形}} and featured various blade shapes, ranging from straight to inward-curving edges. They were often included as {{ill|grave goods|ja|副葬品}}. During the {{ill|Warring States period|ja|戦国時代 (中国)}}, iron tōsu began to appear. By the Han dynasty, tōsu with inlays, decorative designs, and attached rings for threading cords became common.

=== In Korea and Japan ===
Continental tōsu also made their way to Korea and Japan as imported items.

== In Japan ==

Bronze tōsu, likely acquired through trade with the mainland, were unearthed at the {{ill|Misakiyama site|ja|三崎山遺跡}} in Yusa Town, Yamagata Prefecture, dating back approximately 3,000 years.<ref>Yokoyama Akio, Kondō Keishin, Itō Kiyoshi, and Watanabe Shinobu, "The History of Yamagata Prefecture," pp. 21-22.</ref> In the late {{ill|Jōmon period|ja|縄文時代}}, imitation bronze tōsu made of {{ill|stone|ja|石剣}} have been discovered.<ref>"Japanese Archaeology II: The Jōmon Period," edited by Kamaki Yoshimasa, Kawade Shobō, 1965, pp. 430-431.</ref> 

