Bronze tōsu, likely acquired through trade with the mainland, were unearthed at the {{ill|Misakiyama site|ja|三崎山遺跡|qq=draft}} in Yusa Town, Yamagata Prefecture, dating back approximately 3,000 years.<ref>Yokoyama Akio, Kondō Keishin, Itō Kiyoshi, and Watanabe Shinobu, "The History of Yamagata Prefecture," pp. 21-22.</ref> In the late {{ill|Jōmon period|ja|縄文時代|qq=draft}}, imitation bronze tōsu made of {{ill|stone|ja|石剣|qq=draft}} have been discovered.<ref>"Japanese Archaeology II: The Jōmon Period," edited by Kamaki Yoshimasa, Kawade Shobō, 1965, pp. 430-431.</ref>
In the {{ill|Kofun period|ja|古墳時代|qq=draft}}, the introduction of {{ill|iron tools|ja|鉄器|qq=draft}} began. By the 4th century, tōsu were included as grave goods in {{ill|kofun|ja|古墳|1=Kofun|qq=draft}} tombs, such as those found at the {{ill|Tsubai Ōtsukayama Kofun|ja|椿井大塚山古墳|qq=draft}} in Kyoto Prefecture. By the 6th century, tōsu became widely used, with some adorned with gold-bronze decorations or stored in scabbards matching the blade. Handles were sometimes embellished with patterns.
Although {{ill|bladed weapons|ja|刀剣|qq=draft}} are commonly associated with warriors and military officials,<ref>"Nihon Shisō Taikei: Ritsuryō," Iwanami Shoten, 1976.</ref> in ancient East Asia, tōsu symbolized {{ill|literati|ja|文人|qq=draft}} and civil officials. During periods when {{ill|mokkan|ja|木簡|qq=draft}} and {{ill|bamboo slips|ja|竹簡|qq=draft}} were widely used due to the rarity of {{ill|paper|ja|紙|qq=draft}}, tōsu were essential for correcting mistakes by shaving off errors. Tōsu preserved in the {{ill|Shōsōin|ja|正倉院|qq=draft}} are classified not as weapons but as {{ill|stationery|ja|文房具|qq=draft}}.
