'''Tōsu''' (刀子) is a type of [[:en:Hand tool|tool]] used for cutting and shaving, among other tasks. It is similar to the modern {{ill|kogatana|ja|小刀|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/kogatana|qq=}} (small utility knife). Its length typically ranges between 15 and 30 cm.
== Overview ==
=== General Use === Iron tools are generally classified as {{ill|agricultural implements|ja|農機具|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/agricultural implements|qq=}}, tools for crafting, or implements related to the production of {{ill|ironware|ja|鉄器|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/ironware|qq=}}. However, the tōsu does not fit neatly into these categories and is instead considered a multi-purpose tool. While commonly used as a crafting implement, it also served as a kitchen tool, a {{ill|cosmetic|ja|化粧|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/cosmetic|qq=|comment=enwiki is a redirect}} accessory, a [[:en:Ceremonial weapon|ritual implement]], or even as a knife for shaving the surface of [[:en:Mokkan|mokkan]] (wooden tablets used for writing).
=== In China === In China, bronze tōsu have been discovered from the early [[:en:Erlitou culture|Erlitou culture]] during the [[:en:Shang dynasty|Shang dynasty]] period. These tōsu were typically {{ill|ring-headed|ja|環頭形|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/ring-headed|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} and featured various blade shapes, ranging from straight to inward-curving edges. They were often included as [[:en:Grave goods|grave goods]]. During the [[:en:Warring States period|Warring States period]], iron tōsu began to appear. By the Han dynasty, tōsu with inlays, decorative designs, and attached rings for threading cords became common.
=== In Korea and Japan === Continental tōsu also made their way to Korea and Japan as imported items.
== In Japan ==
Bronze tōsu, likely acquired through trade with the mainland, were unearthed at the {{ill|Misakiyama site|ja|三崎山遺跡|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Misakiyama site|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} in Yusa Town, Yamagata Prefecture, dating back approximately 3,000 years.<ref>Yokoyama Akio, Kondō Keishin, Itō Kiyoshi, and Watanabe Shinobu, "The History of Yamagata Prefecture," pp. 21-22.</ref> In the late [[:en:Jōmon period|Jōmon period]], imitation bronze tōsu made of {{ill|stone|ja|石剣|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/stone|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 石刀・石剣}} have been discovered.<ref>"Japanese Archaeology II: The Jōmon Period," edited by Kamaki Yoshimasa, Kawade Shobō, 1965, pp. 430-431.</ref>
In the [[:en:Kofun period|Kofun period]], the introduction of {{ill|iron tools|ja|鉄器|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/iron tools|qq=}} began. By the 4th century, tōsu were included as grave goods in [[:en:Kofun|Kofun]] tombs, such as those found at the [[:en:Tsubai Ōtsukayama Kofun|Tsubai Ōtsukayama Kofun]] in Kyoto Prefecture. By the 6th century, tōsu became widely used, with some adorned with gold-bronze decorations or stored in scabbards matching the blade. Handles were sometimes embellished with patterns.
Although [[:en:Sword|bladed weapons]] are commonly associated with warriors and military officials,<ref>"Nihon Shisō Taikei: Ritsuryō," Iwanami Shoten, 1976.</ref> in ancient East Asia, tōsu symbolized {{ill|literati|ja|文人|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/literati|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 文人 (曖昧さ回避)}} and civil officials. During periods when [[:en:Mokkan|mokkan]] and {{ill|bamboo slips|ja|竹簡|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/bamboo slips|qq=}} were widely used due to the rarity of [[:en:Paper|paper]], tōsu were essential for correcting mistakes by shaving off errors. Tōsu preserved in the [[:en:Shōsōin|Shōsōin]] are classified not as weapons but as [[:en:Stationery|stationery]].
